  <div class="textDiv">
    <h2>Berlin Free Gem — RAW Energy on Revaler Straße</h2>
    <p class="sectionText">
      East Berlin hides a place where the city's raw spirit lives in full color.
      Just off Revaler Straße, the former train repair yard known as RAW Gelände
      has transformed into one of the city's most eclectic cultural spots. What
      looks like an abandoned industrial site is now a maze of graffiti-covered
      walls, hidden corners, and open-air art. Every surface is painted, tagged,
      layered, and repainted — a free gallery that shifts with the city itself.
    </p>
    <p class="sectionText">
      In the middle of it all stands Urban Spree, part gallery, part music
      venue, part garden hangout. Here you'll find exhibitions, murals, and
      installations that change regularly — some free to explore, others
      spilling outside for everyone to see. Around the area, you'll stumble upon
      bars, cafés, food stalls, and even a skate hall. Cassiopeia offers
      concerts and club nights, while tucked in between it all you might spot
      one of Berlin's quirkiest attractions: a tiny disco hidden inside an old
      phone booth.
    </p>
    <p class="sectionText">
      What makes this a true Free Gem is the art you don't have to pay for. The
      walls themselves are alive, constantly rewritten by Berlin's graffiti and
      street art community. Walking through RAW feels like stepping inside a
      living canvas — chaotic, unfinished, always changing. Whether you're there
      for the galleries, a beer in the sun, or just to wander, the area is proof
      of how Berlin keeps creating in public.
    </p>
  </div>
